		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/15/opinion/nyto-floods/nyto-floods-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/15/opinion/nyto-floods/nyto-floods-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/15/opinion/nyto-floods/nyto-floods-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003002235" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Robert Stolarik for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/15/when-climate-change-floods-your-heart/" data-title="When Climate Change Floods Your Heart" data-description="As politicians argue over the science of climate change, others are starting to talk about its emotional impact. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2100, I will live in Florida.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let me backtrack: Unless longevity research makes some big strides in the next few decades, Iâll probably be dead by 2100. Nor do I have any plans to retire to Palm Beach in my late 110s. But if I somehow survive, and if I stay in New York City, my experience will be Floridian: According to an interactiveÂ <a href="//www.climatecentral.org/news/summer-temperatures-co2-emissions-1001-cities-16583">map</a>Â created by Climate Central, a Manhattan summer at the end of this century will feel like a summer in Lehigh Acres, about 90 miles south of Sarasota.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And what if in my extreme old age I decide to return to the city of my childhood, Los Angeles? As it turns out, Los Angeles in 2100 will feel like the Florida city of Fountainbleau. According to Climate Central at least, global warming is slowly turning all the places I have ever loved into Florida.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The metaphor of physical displacement feels like an apt one for what appears to be happening to our weather: The places we live are not what they once were. While politicians debate the existence of climate change (or, increasingly, move on to debating whether to do anything about it), other narratives are just starting to get attention: Those that deal with how it feels when what we once relied on â the length of the winter, say, or the depth of a river â seems to shift around us.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a May story for The Globe and Mail, Gayle MacDonald <a href="//www.theglobeandmail.com/life/health-and-fitness/health/youth-anxiety-on-the-rise-amid-changing-climate/article18372258/">quotes</a> Sammy McLean, a 14-year-old girl whose Calgary home was damaged by a recent flood:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI used to think the rivers were so pretty. It made me not like them any more. I thought the water was going to take away the whole house â and my bedroom.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. MacDonald also talks to Chris Saade, a therapist who has treated kids anxious about climate change. He says:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe tell them grief is a normal response of the human psyche when a loss is happening, whether itâs personal or, in this case, a global loss in terms of the environment. If we donât feel grief, at the end of the day, we wonât do anything.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others, too, are beginning to ask how grief affects our response to the climate. Katharine M. Preston, a preacher and writer, <a href="//www.utne.com/environment/the-reality-of-climate-change-zm0z13ndzlin.aspx#axzz37BuvZUnm">addresses</a> these issues in an essay at Utne Reader (Update: The piece was <a href="//sojo.net/magazine/2013/08/mourning-earth">originally published</a> in Sojourners):</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe rarely talk about loss, grief, and climate change. The losses come in many forms. Clearly the victims of weather-related events, such as Hurricanes Katrina and Sandy, grieve deeply when faced with the immediate losses of homes and neighborhoods. People drawing their livelihoods from the land and sea notice changes that will eventually eliminate that way of life for them, at least in that place. Some of us may have chosen changes in lifestyles to reduce our carbon footprint; it is something we do out of love, but there can still be accompanying feelings of loss.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She fears that these feelings may be immobilizing for some and calls upon readers to âadapt to an environment in which our traditional relationship with the Earth has been replaced with a new one. Everything must change, from how we dry our clothes to the underlying assumptions about our economy.â She asks, âInstead of guilt, fear, and depression, can we face our profound loss, talk about it, acknowledge our grief, and move forward within this new community?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Preston also cites Steve Running, an ecology professor who delivered a popular talk calledÂ âThe Five Stages of Climate Griefâ in 2007. Channeling Elisabeth KÃ¼bler-Ross, he <a href="//www.ntsg.umt.edu/files/5StagesClimateGrief.htm">argued</a> that policy makers needed to move beyond the stages of denial and depression into something more productive:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe really need most of our political, business and intellectual leaders to reach Stage 5 ACCEPTANCE in order to move forward, as a nation, and as a global citizenry. There is no guarantee that we can successfully stop global warming, but doing nothing given our present knowledge is unconscionable. How otherwise can we look into our grandchildrenâs eyes?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others may prefer to grieve without necessarily trying to fix the problem. In The New York Times Magazine in April, Daniel Smith <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/20/magazine/its-the-end-of-the-world-as-we-know-it-and-he-feels-fine.html?module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=Magazine&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article">profiled</a> Paul Kingsnorth, the author of a manifesto called âUncivilizationâ and a critic of the idea that technological solutions can reverse the effects of climate change. Mr. Smith wrote:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âKingsnorth would agree with the need for grief but not with the idea that it must lead to change â at least not the kind of change that mainstream environmental groups pursue. âWhat do you do,â he asked, âwhen you accept that all of these changes are coming, things that you value are going to be lost, things that make you unhappy are going to happen, things that you wanted to achieve you canât achieve, but you still have to live with it, and thereâs still beauty, and thereâs still meaning, and there are still things you can do to make the world less bad? And thatâs not a series of questions that have any answers other than peopleâs personal answers to them. Selfishly itâs just a process Iâm going through.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Meanwhile Zadie Smith, in an essay at The New York Review of Books, <a href="//www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/apr/03/elegy-countrys-seasons/">imagines</a> what she might tell her (at this point, notional) granddaughter in 2050 about climate change and how we felt about it in 2014:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs important to remember that the necessary conditions of our lives â those things that seem to us unavoidably to be the case â are not only debated by physicists and philosophers but exist, irrationally, in the minds of the rest of us, beneath contempt intellectually, perhaps, but we still experience them as permanent facts. The climate was one of those facts. We did not think it could change. That is, we always knew we could do a great deal of damage to this planet, but even the most hubristic among us had not imagined we would ever be able to fundamentally change its rhythms and character, just as a child who has screamed all day at her father still does not expect to see him lie down on the kitchen floor and weep.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Smith sees our emotions as both an impediment and a goad to action. On the one hand, we may be a little bit attached to end-of-the-world narratives, as long as theyâre vague enough.Â On the other, changes in the things we thought could never change may propel us through sorrow to solution. She imagines telling her young descendant:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn the end, the only thing that could create the necessary traction in our minds was the intimate loss of the things we loved. Like when the seasons changed in our beloved little island, or when the lights went out on the fifteenth floor, or the day I went into an Italian garden in early July, with its owner, a woman in her eighties, and upon seeing the scorched yellow earth and withered roses, and hearing what only the really old people will confess âÂ <i>in all my years Iâve never seen anything like itÂ </i>â I found my mind finally beginning to turn from the elegiacÂ <i>what have we done</i>Â to the practicalÂ <i>what can we do?</i>â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If I somehow live until 2100 Iâll have time not just for granddaughters but for great-great-granddaughters. Maybe by then all of us, living in our various Floridas, will have sorted out our feelings and determined what, if anything, we can do with them.</p>
	</div>
